T1  - Financial structure and reforms in Central and Eastern Europe in the 1980s
AU  - Catte, Pietro
AU  - Mastropasqua, Cristina
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 17
IS  - 5
SP  - 785
EP  - 817
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(93)90060-Q
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669390060Q
AB  - The paper analyzes the evolution of the financial structure of the countries of Central and Eastern Europe during the 1980s. In these countries the financial system is assigned a limited and mostly passive function; this needs to be seen in the context of the allocative system of centrally planned economies, where the transfer of financial resources between sectors is largely performed directly by the State through the price system, taxes and subsidies. The analysis focuses specifically on Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia. The development of their financial structure is assessed through a number of quantitative indicators. We find that the partial economic and financial reforms introduced in Hungary and Poland before 1989 did not substantially modify the role and performance of the financial system, whose size in relation to the real economy remained modest. At the same time, however, the reforms exacerbated some of the distortions of the planned system and generated larger macroeconomic imbalances, the effects of which tend to cloud the interpretation of financial indicators. At the end of 1980 the banking systems of Hungary and Poland, although formally decentralized, continued to allocate credit mostly according to automatic criteria and had virtually no experience in assessing and monitoring borrowers and investment projects; in this respect, they differed little from that of Czechoslovakia, which remained based on the classic model of a single State bank.
ER  - 

