T1  - Reconstruction of the financial system in East Germany: Description and comparison with Eastern Europe
AU  - Wagner, Helmut
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 17
IS  - 5
SP  - 1001
EP  - 1019
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(93)90068-O
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669390068O
AB  - First the reconstruction process of the financial system in East Germany is described. It is shown that the goal of quickly constructing an efficient banking system that corresponds to Western standards has largely been reached. Then the speciality or difference of the East German development in comparison with other transformation countries in Eastern Europe is discussed. The decisive difference is argued to have been the total adoption of the West German political, economic and legal order by East Germany after the monetary, economic and social union with West Germany in 1990. Besides, after this union, West German banks have continuously gained influence and dominance in the East German financial market by having had timely set up branches of their own all over East Germany and by having transferred substantial resources of capital and qualified personnel as well as managerial know-how to them. Last but not least, in accordance with the State Treaty of May 1990, a security arrangement for the credit system in East Germany was established: in order to safeguard the existence of the banks in East Germany, their solvency in contact with domestic and foreign creditors has been guaranteed by the (then West) German State.
ER  - 
